--- body ---
## Context

The Oeconomia manuscript (intellectual history, submitted 2026-03-18)
argues that climate finance crystallized as an economic object by ~2009.
This companion paper provides the quantitative backbone: a framework
for detecting and validating structural change in text corpora, applied
to the climate finance literature.

Adapted from ChatGPT note (docs/ChatGPT-20260415-MethodForAutoPeriodization-v1.md).
Lean design: one lead method per representation layer, permutation
Z-scores for inference, transition zones (not point breaks).

## Epistemic stance

The method detects candidate structural changes and validates them
across independent representations. It does not claim to uniquely
discover a true periodization. Social change is fuzzy — we report
transition zones (year ranges where Z > 2), not single break years.

## Method panel (6 methods, 3 layers)

Chosen for stability at small n and growing corpus. Permutation Z-scores
normalize all methods against sample-size variation.

| Layer | Lead | Robustness | Interpretation |
|-------|------|------------|----------------|
| Embedding | Energy distance | C2ST on PCA-32 | Discriminative directions + documents |
| Lexical | JS divergence | C2ST on TF-IDF | Discriminative terms |
| Graph | Community div (Louvain+JS) | Spectral gap | Community membership shifts |

**Design choices:**
- Energy (not MMD): no kernel, no bandwidth, no hyperparameters, stable at n=30
- Sliding windows, w=3 years (local change detection, not cumulative)
- Z > 2 threshold (p ≈ 0.023, conservative one-sided)
- Transition zones: year ranges where Z exceeds threshold
- Multi-signal validation: do transition zones from independent layers overlap?
- Two-pass censored-gap confirmation: detect zones, then censor transition
  years and retest. Z still high → discontinuity. Z drops → gradual drift.
- Discriminative terms: both log-odds (Monroe et al. 2008) and C2ST
  coefficients — decide which to foreground after seeing results

**Not in the companion paper:**
The 15-method divergence zoo (MMD, Wasserstein, Fréchet, L2/L3,
G1/G3-G8), PELT/DynP/KernelCPD changepoint detection, and MC size-bias
characterization are internal engineering artifacts. They live in
`content/technical-report.qmd` as includes (ticket 0028), not as a
supplement to this paper. Lean over comprehensive.

## Paper structure (companion-paper.qmd)

1. Introduction — endogenous periodization, multi-layer approach
2. Related work (keep existing §2.1-2.4, add C2ST reference)
3. Data (reuse §3, update corpus stats)
4. Method
   - 4.1 Objective and epistemic stance
   - 4.2 Representations (embedding, lexical, graph)
   - 4.3 Temporal segmentation (sliding windows, w=3)
   - 4.4 Distributional comparison (Energy, JS, Louvain+JS)
   - 4.5 Statistical inference (permutation Z-scores)
   - 4.6 Transition zone detection + multi-signal validation
   - 4.7 Censored-gap confirmation (two-pass)
   - 4.8 Robustness (subsampling, sensitivity, PELT)
   - 4.9 Interpretation (terms, documents, communities)
5. Results — applied to climate finance corpus
6. Discussion — generalizability, limitations, growth-bias honesty
7. Conclusion

